[zero_shot][olmo3_7b_instruct][mmlu] sample 1/200 done id=mmlu_validation_1 prediction='To determine the order of the factor group \\(\\mathbb{Z}_6 / \\langle 3 \\rangle\\), first identify the subgroup \\(\\langle 3 \\rangle\\) in \\(\\mathbb{Z}_6\\). The element 3 in \\(\\mathbb{Z}_6\\) has order 2 because \\(3 \\times 2 = 6 \\equiv 0 \\pmod{6}\\), and no smaller positive multiple equals 0. Thus, \\(\\langle 3 \\rangle = \\{0, 3}\\), which has order 2. By the First Isomorphism Theorem, the order of the quotient group \\(\\mathbb{Z}_6 / \\langle 3 \\rangle\\) equals the index of \\(\\langle 3\\rangle\\) in \\(\\mathbb{Z}_6\\). The order of \\(\\mathbb{Z}_6\\) is 6, so the index is \\(6 / 2 = 3\\). Alternatively, listing cosets: 0·3 = {0}, 1·3 = {3}, 2·3 = {4}, 4·3 = {2}, 5·3 = {5}. These are five distinct elements,' gold='B' correct=False
[zero_shot][olmo3_7b_instruct][mmlu] sample 2/200 start id=mmlu_validation_6
[zero_shot][olmo3_7b_instruct][mmlu] sample 2/200 done id=mmlu_validation_6 prediction='Let’s analyze each statement in turn.\n\n**Statement 1:** If a and b are elements of finite order in an Abelian group, then |ab| = lcm(|a|, |b|).\n\n- In an Abelian group, the order of a product is the least common multiple of the orders of the factors. That is, if |a| = m and |b| = n, then (ab)^(lcm(m,n)) = a^(lcm(m,n)) b^(lcm(m,n)) = (e^m)^{lcm(m,n)} (e^n)^{lcm(m,n)} = e^{m* lcm(m,n)/m} e^{n* lcm(m,n)/n} = e^{lcm(m,n)} = e, so |ab| divides lcm(m,n). The converse also holds because if (ab)^k = e, then a^k b^k = e, so m and n both divide k, hence lcm(m,n) is the minimal such k. Thus |ab| = lcm(m,n).\n- This is true in any Abelian group.\n\n**Statement 2:** If g is a group element and g^n = e, then |g| = n.\n\n-' gold='B' correct=False
