[zero_shot][olmo3_7b_instruct][mmlu] sample 46/200 done id=mmlu_validation_330 prediction="The question asks for the average mass of one carbon atom in grams.  \nWe know that the molar mass of carbon (the mass of one mole of carbon atoms) is approximately 12 grams per mole.  \nBy definition, the molar mass (in grams per mole) is numerically equal to the atomic mass (in atomic mass units, amu) of the element.  \nTherefore, the average mass of a single carbon atom in amu is 12 amu.  \nHowever, the question specifically asks for the average mass of a single carbon atom, but measured in grams.  \nBut the only option that makes sense in the context of the choices given is the relationship between molar mass and atomic mass.  \nOption D states the mass in grams of the most abundant isotope of carbon (which is carbon-12, with a mass of 12 g/mol), and since the average mass in amu per atom is numerically equal to the molar mass in g/mol divided by Avogadro's number, but the question's wording is tricky.  \nHowever, the standard fact taught is that the molar mass (in g/mol) of an element equals the atomic mass (in amu) of its atoms, so the average mass in amu" gold='A' correct=False
