[zero_shot][olmo3_7b_instruct][mmlu] sample 47/200 done id=mmlu_validation_333 prediction="To determine the correct atomic radius and first ionization energy for sodium, we start by recalling that sodium (Na) has an atomic number of 11 and is in Group 1 of the periodic table. Group 1 metals are known for having low ionization energies because their single valence electron is far from the nucleus, and they have large atomic radii due to the high number of electron shells.\n\nGiven:\n- First ionization energy of sodium = 496 kJ/mol\n- Atomic radius of sodium = 186 pm (this is the actual value, but the question asks us to match it to the options)\n\nLet's analyze the options:\n\n**Option A:** 160 pm, 737 kJ/mol  \n- 160 pm is smaller than the actual radius (186 pm), which would mean a higher effective nuclear charge and a much higher ionization energy. 737 kJ/mol is also higher than 496 kJ/mol. This is inconsistent with sodium's properties.\n\n**Option B:** 86 pm, 398 kJ/mol  \n- 86 pm is similar to the radius of lithium (which is about 152 pm, but alkali metals like potassium are around 190 pm). 86 pm is more like that of helium or maybe a transition" gold='A' correct=False
