[zero_shot][olmo3_7b_instruct][mmlu] sample 50/200 done id=mmlu_validation_350 prediction="To determine which function grows the slowest as \\( N \\) approaches infinity, we compare the growth rates of the given options:\n\n- **O(N^(1/2))**: Square root growth, increases but slower than linear.\n- **O(N^(1/4))**: Fourth root growth, even slower than square root.\n- **O(N^(1/N))**: Exponent is \\( 1/N \\), which approaches 0 as \\( N \\) grows. So, \\( N^{1/N} \\) approaches 1 (since any number to the power of 0 is 1), and grows extremely slowly—much slower than constant.\n- **O(N)**: Linear growth, the fastest among the options.\n\nAs \\( N \\) becomes very large, the function \\( N^{1/N} \\) approaches 1 and increases very slowly (for example, at N=16, it's 16^(1/16) ≈ 1.189; at N=1000, it's about 1.032). In contrast, constants (like 1) grow at the same rate, and all other options (A and B) grow faster than this. Therefore, **O(N^(1/N))** grows the slowest." gold='C' correct=False
