[zero_shot][olmo3_7b_instruct][mmlu] sample 52/200 done id=mmlu_validation_393 prediction='Let\'s analyze each statement about congressional committees:\n\nI. "The committee chairpersons always belong to the majority party."  \nThis is not true. Committee chairs can be from the majority or the minority party, depending on the political makeup of the committee and the desires of the party in power at the time. There are examples where a minority party member is chosen as a committee chair.\n\nII. "Seats on each committee are divided between the two major parties in exact proportion to their representation in Congress."  \nThis is generally false. While there is a tendency for committee membership to reflect the overall party balance in Congress, it is not always exact. Committees can have members from both parties who may not correspond precisely to the Senate and House party ratios, especially in the case of non-partisan or special committees.\n\nIII. "They recommend whether Congress should pass various pieces of legislation, and those recommendations are always approved by the full congressional body."  \nThis is also not true. Committee recommendations on legislation are not always approved by the full chamber. Congress can choose to overrule, amend, or ignore committee recommendations.\n\nIV. (Not listed as a choice, so we ignore it for this question.)\n\nFrom the above, only statement II is partially accurate but not strictly true in all cases. However' gold='A' correct=False
